post_text:
Get ready to be informed, entertained and inspired at the LivingWorks Youth Summit, a live-streaming online mental health event being created specifically for grades 7 to 12 students! This virtual summit will take place on Sept. 15 for all middle and high school students in California.

This suicide prevention training for students is part of a free online program launched this year by California Department of Education and San Diego County Office of Education. Especially during the #COVID19 pandemic, having students and teachers trained to recognize when someone is struggling and connect them to help empowers the whole school community to come together and support those at risk.

Learn more about the event at www.lwyouthsummit.com and educators look for a code next month to distribute to students next month. ‚û°Ô∏è Save the date (Sept. 15 from 1 to 2 p.m.) on your calendar and spread the word about this event.

#suicideprevention #suicidepreventiontraining #students #middleschool #highschool

ICOE is excited to announce the rolling out of a new professional learning experience: Asynchronous vs. Synchronous Instruction.

‚Ä¢ Join us as we lead an engaging, hands-on experience that showcases how to powerfully merge asynchronous with synchronous teaching in order to maximize time spent with students.
‚Ä¢ As a participant, you will experience three short synchronous lessons in the areas of ELA, Math, and Science after completing an asynchronous lesson for each at home.
‚Ä¢ Participants will also have time for collaboration and will walk away with strategies to apply in their remote or face-to-face classroom immediately.

OUR VOICES COUNT! - Unincorporated areas make up most of our region. They are not part of any official city, with oversight by the county. Residents of unincorporated areas receive the Census through the Update Leave system, which delivers the Census to communities that don't generally receive mail at their home.

If you have friends and family that live in any of these hard to count communities, give them a call to see if they have completed the census and help them get counted!

Visit 2020Census.gov or call 844-330-2020.

#ICount #KidsCountToo #ImperialCounts #CensusWeekofAction #CountMe2020 #EveryoneCounts #CaliforniaCounts #2020census #CaliforniaforAll Count Me 2020: San Diego and Imperial Counties Census Outreach Coalition

Chairman of the Board and District 2 Supervisor, Luis A. Plancarte stated, ‚ÄúWe received verbal notification minutes prior to Governor Newsom‚Äôs public announcement. A live press conference to provide updated information will be held at 6:00 p.m. and broadcast on the Imperial County website at http://imperial.granicus.com/ViewPublisher.php?view_id=2 and Facebook @ImperialCntyCA.

FREE RESOURCE:
‚Ä¢ Continuity of Learning: Playbooks for COVID-19 ‚Ä¢

To assist LEA leaders planning for teaching and learning in this new COVID-19 context, the CCEE has created two easy-to-understand online Playbooks: the Distance Learning Playbook and the Hybrid Learning Playbook. Each suggests nine areas of focus to guide planning: setting goals, creating schedules, communicating with families, assessing student needs, supporting social-emotional learning, building capacity, supporting English language learners, supporting students with special needs, and leveraging ancillary programs. Both also bring a special equity lens to the nine areas and offer practical resources, tools, and tips leadership teams can consider adopting.

Access Playbooks: ‚û°Ô∏è https://k12playbook.ccee-ca.org/

California Collaborative for Educational Excellence
San Diego County Office of Education Riverside county Office Of Education.

#2020Census Progress Update:
The protests happening across the nation are part of a long march toward justice. We must continue to build power within and between our communities. #BlackLivesMatter ‚Äì and they deserve to be counted.

Black communities are historically undercounted in the Census. We must ensure that black communities are counted in the 2020 Census so that they are seen, heard, and represented.

Make your voices heard by taking the 2020 Census. Complete yours online at 2020Census.gov or by phone at 844-330-2020.

Due to Coronavirus (COVID-19), children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals at school will receive additional food benefits. These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT or P-EBT benefits. P-EBT benefits help families in California buy food when schools are closed because of the coronavirus emergency. Families may receive up to $365 per eligible child on their P-EBT card to use on food and groceries. The online application will be available beginning May 22, 2020 at ca.p-ebt.org.

Families with children who get CalFresh, Medi-Cal or Foster Care benefits do not need to apply. Most will get their P-EBT card in the mail during the month of May.

Reference Guide: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1dYCwMyaldMVrpNgsz8NV7pzdTjfsJvWP/view?usp=sharing

Calexico High School hosted a drive-thru event for students that were part of the Unified PE class during the year. This event gave an opportunity to students and staff to say ‚Äúhi‚Äù to each other as well as pick up a Unified PE shirt. Parents, students, and staff were very excited to see each other, even if it was from a distance!

Unified PE is a physical education class offered at Calexico High School during the school year where students with and without special needs participate in physical education activities together. Approximately half of the class is comprised of students from ICOE and the other half of students from the general education population at CHS.

Through participation in this class, #inclusion increases and bullying decreases; both groups of students benefit immensely from Unified PE!

Calexico High School was recently honored as a ‚ÄúUnified Champion School‚Äù through the Special Olympics, recognizing CHS for their school-wide inclusionary practices such as Unified PE, the Circle of Friends program, and more!

ICOE‚Äôs Valley Academy School was awarded a grant through the Career Technical Education Facilities Program (CTEFP) to modernize its facilities and begin a CTE course in Heating, Ventilation, and Air Conditioning (HVAC). This exciting pathway will be the first of its kind in Imperial County, preparing students to fill a growing labor need in the area of HVAC.

Programs like these can change the trajectory of our students‚Äô lives. Ultimately, it is ICOE‚Äôs desire that our students enter the workforce prepared and ready to succeed.

Imperial County Public Health Department
March 31 at 6:49 PM ¬∑

The Imperial County Health Officer has issued an amended Health Officer Order which goes into effect, Wednesday, April 1, 2020, and will remain in effect until further notice. The amended order reiterates the stay at home order for all residents living in Imperial County, except to attend to critical needs such as getting food, medications or medical assistance. Exceptions are also made for essential workers employed in the essential critical infrastructure sector as identified by the California Department of Public Health (CDPH). Additionally, all businesses in Imperial County are to remain closed except for those determined to be part of the essential critical infrastructure sector. The full order can be found on the Imperial County Public Health Department website. http://www.icphd.org/health-information-and-resources/healthy-facts/covid-19/general-public/
